California.  A name that conjures images of sunshine, innovation, and a certain… relentless optimism.  Though, if you ask me, it’s more a vast, complex organism that’s perpetually trying to outrun its own shadow.  It's a state that’s seen more gold than a dragon’s hoard and more ambition than a startup pitch meeting.

## U.S. State

This is, of course, about [California](/U.S._state), the one that dominates the western seaboard. It’s not just *a* state; it’s *the* state, in many respects. For those who might be confused, perhaps lost in the sheer volume of information available, this article is specifically about the U.S. state. Any other California you might be thinking of – well, that’s why they have [California (disambiguation)](/California_(disambiguation)). Don't expect me to hold your hand through that.

### State

[California](/U.S._state) is, undeniably, a [state](/U.S._state) within the United States. It’s a fact that’s both obvious and, frankly, a bit redundant to state. But here we are.

#### Flag

The [flag](/Flag_of_California) – the one with the bear. A rather stoic creature, that bear. Not exactly leaping for joy, is it? More like a silent, furry guardian. It suggests a certain primal strength, perhaps a defiance against the encroaching tide of civilization, or maybe just a very well-fed bear.

#### Seal

Then there’s the [Seal](/Seal_of_California). A rather busy affair, isn't it? A goddess, Minerva, looking formidable, a grizzly bear, naturally, and all sorts of symbols of prosperity. It’s a visual manifesto, really, attempting to capture the essence of a place that’s constantly reinventing itself.

#### Nickname

They call it "The Golden State." &#91;4&#93; &#160; Apt, I suppose, given the gold rush and all that. But "golden" can also imply something superficial, something that gleams but lacks substance. California’s got plenty of substance, but it’s also got a lot of glitter.

#### Motto

"[Eureka](/Eureka_(word))". &#91;5&#93; &#160; "I have found it." A rather triumphant declaration, isn't it? As if the ultimate discovery has been made. Perhaps they found the perfect climate, the ultimate economic engine, or just a really good taco truck. Given the state's history, it's probably a bit of all of the above, and none of them, simultaneously.

#### Anthem

And the anthem? "[I Love You, California](/I_Love_You,_California)". A rather direct, almost pleading sentiment. It’s a declaration of affection, a love song to a place that inspires such devotion, and sometimes, such exasperation.

### Location

It’s situated in the [Western United States](/Western_United_States), hugging the [Pacific Coast](/West_Coast_of_the_United_States). Borders with [Oregon](/Oregon) to the north, [Nevada](/Nevada) and [Arizona](/Arizona) to the east, and a rather significant international border with [Mexico](/Mexico) to the south, specifically the state of [Baja California](/Baja_California). It's a geographical nexus, a place where cultures and economies converge, often with predictable friction.

### Statehood

It was admitted to the Union on [September 9, 1850](/An_Act_for_the_Admission_of_the_State_of_California), making it the 31st state. A rather pivotal moment, I imagine, transitioning from [Mexican Cession](/Mexican_Cession) and [unorganized territory](/Interim_government_of_California) to full-fledged statehood. A testament to rapid expansion, and perhaps a bit of manifest destiny thrown in for good measure.

### Capital and Major Cities

The [capital](/List_of_capitals_in_the_United_States) is [Sacramento](/Sacramento,_California). A rather unassuming choice, perhaps, given the glitz and glamour elsewhere. The [largest city](/List_of_largest_cities_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_population) is [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), a sprawling metropolis that seems to defy gravity and logic in equal measure. And the [largest county](/List_of_the_most_populous_counties_by_U.S._state) is, predictably, [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles_County). The [largest metro](/Statistical_area_(United_States)) and [urban](/List_of_United_States_urban_areas) areas? [Greater Los Angeles](/Greater_Los_Angeles), of course. It’s a region that defines "sprawl" for the rest of the country.

### Government

The current [Governor](/Governor_of_California) is [Gavin Newsom](/Gavin_Newsom) of the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)). The [Lieutenant Governor](/Lieutenant_Governor_of_California) is [Eleni Kounalakis](/Eleni_Kounalakis), also a Democrat. The [Legislature](/California_State_Legislature) is bicameral, with a [State Senate](/California_State_Senate) and a [State Assembly](/California_State_Assembly). The [Judiciary](/Judiciary) is headed by the [Supreme Court of California](/Supreme_Court_of_California). California’s U.S. Senators are [Alex Padilla](/Alex_Padilla) and [Adam Schiff](/Adam_Schiff), both Democrats. The U.S. House delegation is predominantly Democratic, with 43 [Democrats](/California_Democratic_Party) and 9 [Republicans](/California_Republican_Party).

### Area and Dimensions

California covers a substantial 163,700 square miles (423,970 km²). &#160; That makes it the [third-largest state by area](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_area). It stretches 760 miles (1,220 km) long and 250 miles (400 km) wide. A significant geographic footprint, capable of housing a multitude of distinct environments.

### Elevation

The average elevation is 2,890 feet (880 m). But averages are for people who like neat, tidy numbers. California’s extremes are far more interesting. The highest point is [Mount Whitney](/Mount_Whitney) at 14,504.6 feet (4,421.0 m) &#91;6&#93; &#91;7&#93; &#91;note 1&#93; &#91;note 2&#93; , and the lowest is [Badwater Basin](/Badwater_Basin) at a rather inhospitable −278.9 feet (−85.0 m) &#91;8&#93; . That's a rather dramatic range, wouldn’t you agree? It's like the state itself can't decide if it wants to be high and mighty or buried deep.

### Population

As of 2024, the population is estimated at 39,431,263 &#91;1&#93; . &#160; That makes it the [largest state by population](/List_of_states_and_territories_of_the_United_States_by_population). The density is about 250 people per square mile (97/km²), placing it at [11th in population density](/List_of_states_and_territories_of_the_United_States_by_population_density).

### Income

The [median household income](/Household_income_in_the_United_States) in 2023 was $95,500 &#91;2&#93; , ranking it [5th](/List_of_U.S._states_and_territories_by_income). High income, high cost of living. It’s a familiar refrain.

### Demonyms

A Californian. Simple enough. Though historically, they also used the Spanish term [Californio](/Californio) for the native-born inhabitants of Mexican California, and the Spanish [Californiano](/Californio) is still in use. It speaks to the layered history of the place.

### Language

[English](/Template:Official_languages_of_U.S._states_and_territories) is the official language. &#160; However, [Spanish](/Spanish_language_in_California) is spoken by a significant portion of the population (28.3%), with other languages making up the remaining 15.6% &#91;3&#93; . It’s a linguistic mosaic, though English remains the dominant tile.

### Time Zone

[UTC−08:00](/UTC%E2%88%9208:00) for [PST](/Pacific_Standard_Time), and [UTC−07:00](/UTC%E2%88%9207:00) for [PDT](/Pacific_Daylight_Time). A rather predictable timezone for the western edge of the continent.

### Abbreviations

The USPS abbreviation is [CA](/List_of_U.S._state_and_territory_abbreviations). The ISO code is [US-CA](/ISO_3166-2:US). Traditional abbreviations include Calif., Cal., and Cali.

### Geography

California’s geography is a study in contrasts. It stretches from the [Pacific Coast](/Coastal_California) with its metropolitan areas to the towering [Sierra Nevada](/Sierra_Nevada) mountains. From the ancient [redwood](/Sequoia_sempervirens) and [Douglas fir](/Douglas_fir) forests in the northwest to the stark beauty of the [Mojave Desert](/Mojave_Desert) in the southeast. It’s a place where extreme weather is the norm, with two-thirds of the nation's [earthquake](/List_of_earthquakes_in_California) risk residing here. &#91;12&#93; The [Central Valley](/Central_Valley_(California)), a vast agricultural region, is the state's heartland. The climate varies wildly, from damp [temperate rainforest](/Temperate_rainforest) to arid [desert](/Desert_climate), and even snowy [alpine](/Alpine_climate) in the mountains. &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13&#93; &#91;13